  <ec2-server-template>
    <created-at type="datetime">2011-12-08T18:55:40Z</created-at>
    <description>A server that provides various necessary services for the SE team.

Currently offers:
Subversion, Gitosis, MrClean

# Subversion #
The server will be setup to offer SVN access over HTTP, authenticated by the credentials supplied in svn/username and svn/password.  By default, this access will be read-only, though that can be overridden by setting the svn/http_read_only dropdown to "false".

It is best practice to leave the HTTP access as read-only, and use svn+ssh to actually checkout and commit code as an authorized user.  In order to permit access for a user, make sure that they exist as a RightScale user with the 'server_login' permission.  Then the users must follow the steps in the [this tutorial](http://support.rightscale.com/12345-FAQs/FAQ_0162_-_How_do_I_generate_my_own_SSH_Key_Pair%3F) to use their local private key for access.

# MrClean #
MrClean can be installed using the mrclean::install_from_svn recipe.  The recipe will accept as input arrays for each of the objects that can be managed by MrClean.  In addition a RightScale username and password is required. 

MrClean can be scheduled to run daily at the time specified by scheduler::default.

# Persistent Storage Backups and DR #
This template leverages the beta Storage Toolkit.  The implementation is a bit awkward in that it requires the block volumes to be created or restored as operational scripts rather than in the boot phase.

This means that other services (like subversion and gitosis), will be setup in ephemeral storage, or on the root partition, then later clobbered by mounting a block device.

Likewise, when booting up a new server which is intended to inherit the persistent data from a previous server, the backed up data will not be added until after the server is up and running, and the appropriate block_device restoration script is run. </description>
