  <ec2-server-template>
    <created-at type="datetime">2012-03-01T22:57:34Z</created-at>
    <description>This template installs MongoDB with the option of using EC2 EBS volume(s) as the data store. Ubuntu OS support only at this stage due to kernel requirements(&gt;= 2.6.25)

*----*

How to use in AWS:

Add three servers in a deployment based on this template, each with an Elastic IP.
At the deployment level set the following inputs: *EBS_LINEAGE, EBS_TOTAL_VOLUME_GROUP_SIZE, MONGODB_REPLICA_SET_NAME, MONGODB_REPLSET_NODE_1, MONGODB_REPLSET_NODE_2, MONGODB_REPLSET_NODE_3*

Set *MONGODB_REPLSET_NODE_** inputs to the corresponding public DNS name associated with the Elastic IPs once the servers are launched. For example, in the us-east-1 region, EIP 50.19.0.62 will have this static DNS name associated: ec2-50-19-0-62.compute-1.amazonaws.com. Between the servers in the same region, the DNS name will resolve to the private IP of the server. This will help to lock down the mongodb port(TCP/12345) in the security group.

*----*
Use cases:

1) First launch, no backups to restore from:

    * Launch all servers with EBS_SKIP_MOUNT=false
    * Once the servers are operational, run the 'MongoDB: Initiate replica set' operational script
    * Verify that one server is PRIMARY, the rest are SECONDARY


2) One server crashes and needs to be replaced:

    * Relaunch the server and once operational verify it transitions from RECOVERING to SECONDARY state


3) Replica set needs to restore from backups:

    * Launch server #1 with EBS_SKIP_MOUNT=true, the rest with EBS_SKIP_MOUNT=false
    * Run the 'EBS Stripe volume restore - 11H1' operational script on server #1
    * Run the 'MongoDB: Initiate replica set' operational script on server #2
    * Verify that #1 becomes PRIMARY and the rest SECONDARY


4) Add additional nodes to the replica set:

    * Launch additional nodes with EBS_SKIP_MOUNT=false
    * Once operational execute the 'MongoDB: Add to replica set' operational script. 
     - MONGODB_REPLICA_SET_NODE needs to reference an existing node in the replica set. 
     - MONGODB_NODE_HOSTNAME requires the hostname or IP of the current server. Ex: ec2-50-19-0-62.compute-1.amazonaws.com</description>
    <is-head-version type="boolean">false</is-head-version>
    <nickname>MongoDB v2.0.2 with EBS</nickname>
    <updated-at type="datetime">2012-03-01T22:57:34Z</updated-at>
    <version type="integer">6</version>
    <href>https://my.rightscale.com/api/acct/12345/ec2_server_templates/12345</href>
  </ec2-server-template>
  <ec2-server-template>
    <created-at type="datetime">2012-03-01T22:58:54Z</created-at>
    <description>This template installs MongoDB with the option of using EC2 EBS volume(s) as the data store. Ubuntu OS support only at this stage due to kernel requirements(&gt;= 2.6.25)

*----*

How to use in AWS:

Add three servers in a deployment based on this template, each with an Elastic IP.
At the deployment level set the following inputs: *EBS_LINEAGE, EBS_TOTAL_VOLUME_GROUP_SIZE, MONGODB_REPLICA_SET_NAME, MONGODB_REPLSET_NODE_1, MONGODB_REPLSET_NODE_2, MONGODB_REPLSET_NODE_3*

Set *MONGODB_REPLSET_NODE_** inputs to the corresponding public DNS name associated with the Elastic IPs once the servers are launched. For example, in the us-east-1 region, EIP 50.19.0.62 will have this static DNS name associated: ec2-50-19-0-62.compute-1.amazonaws.com. Between the servers in the same region, the DNS name will resolve to the private IP of the server. This will help to lock down the mongodb port(TCP/12345) in the security group.

*----*
Use cases:

1) First launch, no backups to restore from:

    * Launch all servers with EBS_SKIP_MOUNT=false
    * Once the servers are operational, run the 'MongoDB: Initiate replica set' operational script
    * Verify that one server is PRIMARY, the rest are SECONDARY


2) One server crashes and needs to be replaced:

    * Relaunch the server and once operational verify it transitions from RECOVERING to SECONDARY state


3) Replica set needs to restore from backups:

    * Launch server #1 with EBS_SKIP_MOUNT=true, the rest with EBS_SKIP_MOUNT=false
    * Run the 'EBS Stripe volume restore - 11H1' operational script on server #1
    * Run the 'MongoDB: Initiate replica set' operational script on server #2
    * Verify that #1 becomes PRIMARY and the rest SECONDARY


4) Add additional nodes to the replica set:

    * Launch additional nodes with EBS_SKIP_MOUNT=false
    * Once operational execute the 'MongoDB: Add to replica set' operational script. 
     - MONGODB_REPLICA_SET_NODE needs to reference an existing node in the replica set. 
     - MONGODB_NODE_HOSTNAME requires the hostname or IP of the current server. Ex: ec2-50-19-0-62.compute-1.amazonaws.com</description>
    <is-head-version type="boolean">true</is-head-version>
    <nickname>MongoDB v2.0.2 with EBS v2</nickname>
    <updated-at type="datetime">2012-03-02T23:20:00Z</updated-at>
    <version type="integer">0</version>
